# HTML Standards

## Semantic Elements

Use semantic HTML for better accessibility and SEO.

Prefer: `<header>`, `<nav>`, `<main>`, `<aside>`, `<footer>`, `<article>`, `<section>`

```tsx
// ❌ Bad
<div className={styles.header}>
  <div className={styles.nav}>...</div>
</div>

// ✅ Good
<header className={styles.header}>
  <nav className={styles.nav}>...</nav>
</header>
```

## Element Nesting

Inline elements cannot contain block elements.

```tsx
// ❌ Bad
<span><p>Some text</p></span>

// ✅ Good
<div><p>Some text</p></div>
```

## Minimal DOM

Avoid unnecessary wrapper elements — use CSS Grid/Flexbox in SCSS instead.

```tsx
// ❌ Bad: excessive nesting
<div className={styles.wrapper}>
  <div className={styles.inner}>
    <div className={styles.content}>
      {children}
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

// ✅ Good: flat structure
<section className={styles.content}>
  {children}
</section>
```

## Accessibility

- All `<img>` must have `alt` text
- Interactive elements must be focusable and have visible focus styles
- Use `<button>` for actions, `<a>` for navigation — never `<div onClick>`
- Form inputs need associated `<label>` elements
